# React Rules

## Component Structure
- Use functional components only, no class components
- Use arrow functions for component definitions
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
- Extract complex logic into custom hooks
- Use composition over inheritance

## Hooks
- Custom hooks must start with `use` prefix
- Place hooks in `hooks/` directory
- One hook per file
- Export hooks from `index.ts` for public API
- Follow React hooks rules (only call at top level, only in React functions)

## React Query Hooks
- Use React Query hooks for all data fetching
- Create hooks in `entities/*/hooks/` directory
- Use `useQuery` for fetching data
- Use `useMutation` for mutations (create, update, delete)
- Always use Zod schemas for response validation
- Handle loading, error, and success states properly

## Component Patterns
- Use Server Components by default (Next.js App Router)
- Mark Client Components with `'use client'` directive
- Use `forwardRef` when ref forwarding is needed
- Use `React.memo` only when performance profiling shows it's needed

## Props
- Define props types using TypeScript interfaces or types
- Use destructuring for props
- Provide default values using default parameters
- Use `children` prop for composition

## State Management
- Use React Query for server state
- Use React Context for global client state (auth, theme)
- Use local state (`useState`) for component-specific state
- Avoid prop drilling - use Context or composition

## Event Handlers
- Use arrow functions or `useCallback` for event handlers
- Use `useCallback` when passing handlers to memoized children
- Name handlers with `handle` prefix (e.g., `handleSubmit`, `handleClick`)

## Forms
- Use React Hook Form for all forms
- Use Zod schemas with `@hookform/resolvers/zod` for validation
- Extract form logic into custom hooks when complex

## Performance
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations
- Use `useCallback` for stable function references
- Lazy load heavy components with `next/dynamic`

## Error Handling
- Use error boundaries for component error handling
- Use React Query error handling for API errors
- Display user-friendly error messages
- Log errors appropriately
